<DOC><DOCNO> AP880614-0159 </DOCNO><FILEID>AP-NR-06-14-88 0043EDT</FILEID><FIRST>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2Takes   06-14 0551</FIRST><SECOND>PM-Business Highlights, 2 Takes,0576</SECOND><DATELINE>VIENNA, Austria (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   OPEC members have agreed to extend theirexisting production accord, despite differences over whether toprolong it for three months or six months, according to delegationsources.   The 13-nation Organization of Petroleum Exporting Countries wasto reconvene its regular mid-year conference today. The meeting,which began Saturday, was adjourned Sunday so the ministers couldhold informal talks, which they frequently find more fruitful.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   A federal jury has found that Liggett GroupInc. failed to warn the public about the dangers of cigarettes,marking the first time a tobacco company has been found liable forcontributing to a smoker's death.   The jury awarded $400,000 damages Monday to the husband of RoseCipollone, who died of lung cancer in 1984 at the age of 58. But itheld that Mrs. Cipollone bore 80 percent of the blame for her owndeath.   The jury also exonerated Liggett, Lorillard Inc. and PhilipMorris Inc. of misleading the public about the dangers of smokingand of conspiring to mislead.   It also found that Liggett violated its promise to consumers tomake a safe product, but awarded no damages on that claim.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   U.S. business starts, a barometer of economicactivity and money-making opportunities, declined in the firstthree months of the year for the seventh straight quarterly drop,Dun andamp; Bradstreet Corp. has reported.   The leading business information marketing company said Mondaythe number of new domestic businesses dropped 6.6 percent to 53,382from 57,158 in the first quarter of 1987.</TEXT><DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Manufacturing corporations' after-tax profitsaveraged 6.3 cents per dollar of sales in the first three months ofthe year, up a sharp 43 percent from the fourth quarter, thegovernment has reported.   The Commerce Department said Monday that U.S. manufacturers'after-tax profits totaled a seasonally adjusted $39.4 billion inthe first quarter, compared with $27.4 billion in the fourthquarter, when profits averaged 4.4 cents per dollar of sales.</TEXT><BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE><TEXT>   The Supreme Court says banks can use subsidiaries to underwriteand deal in some securities, reaffirming a lower court decisionthat such activities do not violate a Depression-era law separatingcommercial and investment banking.   The justices on Monday also let stand a ruling that allowsstates to indirectly tax interest paid to banks and other financialinstitutions from investments in Federal Home Loan Bank bonds.   The court also ruled the government may be forced to pay damageswhen a vaccine it licenses causes the disease it was intended toprevent, and it barred states from banning all direct-mailadvertisements sent by lawyers to potential clients.</TEXT><DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE><TEXT>   Carl C. Icahn says he has put $310.2 millioninto an escrow account, promising it would be distributed to TexacoInc. shareholders if he fails to come up with financing for his$60-per-share bid for the oil giant.   In a statement Monday, Icahn also said he had signed a mergeragreement providing for $60 per share in cash to each Texacostockholder, and that it had been sent to the White Plains,N.Y.,-based company.   Last week Icahn said he would put up $300 million to guaranteehis offer, but did not immediately follow through on that pledge.</TEXT><NOTE>MORE</NOTE></DOC>